We run a convolutional neural network (CNN) model on CIFAR-10 dataset using FedAvg. The CNN architecture is shown in TableÂ 2.
To simulate data heterogeneity across clients, we manually distribute the the data to each client in a label-based partition.
Specifically, we split the data according to the classes (pğ‘p) of images that each client has.
Then, we randomly distribute these partitioned data to m=100ğ‘š100m=100 clients such that each client has only pğ‘p classes of images in both training and test data, which causes the heterogeneity of data among different clients.
For example, for p=10ğ‘10p=10, each client contains training/test data samples with ten classes.
Since CIFAR-10 has 101010 classes of images, p=10ğ‘10p=10 is the nearly i.i.d case.
For the remaining pğ‘p, each client contains data samples with class pğ‘p. Therefore, the classes (pğ‘p) of images in each clientâ€™s local dataset can be used to represent the non-i.i.d. degree.
The smaller the pğ‘p-value, the more heterogeneous the data between clients.
